      <section class="detail-block">
        <h2>Application Scenarios</h2>
        <div class="scenario-list">
          <div class="scenario-item">
            <h3>Industrial Bearing Retention in Rotating Assemblies</h3>
            <p>The bearing outer retainer plate positions and secures a bearing's outer race in its housing, preventing axial movement under thrust loads. Precise turning of the plate's outer diameter, bore, and face ensures consistent bearing preload and alignment — critical factors in rotating assembly performance, noise level, and bearing service life.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="scenario-item">
            <h3>Drive System and Transmission Components</h3>
            <p>In drive systems where multiple bearings support a shaft, retainer plates at each bearing position maintain correct axial spacing and prevent bearing creep under cyclic load. Tight tolerance turning of each retainer plate ensures that the bearing arrangement maintains its designed load distribution throughout the service life of the drive.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="scenario-item">
            <h3>Spindle and Precision Axis Assemblies</h3>
            <p>Machine tool spindles and precision linear axes require bearing retention components with surface finish and dimensional accuracy that supports the preload levels needed for high stiffness and low runout. Precision lathe machining of the retainer plate faces and bore provides the surface quality necessary for reliable bearing installation and consistent preload.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="detail-block">
        <h2>Why Precision Turning Matters for Bearing Components</h2>
        <p>Bearing retainer plates that are out of tolerance — in bore diameter, face flatness, or perpendicularity — misload the bearing from the moment of installation. Even small errors translate into increased bearing running temperature, reduced fatigue life, and premature failure. Precision lathe machining to the drawing specification ensures that every retainer plate in a batch installs consistently, providing the bearing with the correct seating and clamping conditions specified by the bearing manufacturer. Contact us with your drawing to discuss production requirements.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="detail-block faq-block">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What is a bearing outer retainer plate?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">A bearing outer retainer plate is a precision machined disc or ring that captures and positions the outer race of a rolling element bearing in its housing. It prevents axial bearing movement under thrust loads and maintains the correct bearing position relative to the shaft and housing.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What tolerances are required for bearing retainer plates?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Bore diameter and face tolerances for bearing retainer plates typically follow ISO fit standards for the bearing outer race diameter (typically H7 or JS7 housing fit). Face flatness and perpendicularity requirements depend on the bearing preload specification. Specify your bearing type and preload class and we will advise on the required tolerances.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What materials are used for bearing retainer plates?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Material depends on the application. Carbon steel is standard for most industrial applications. Stainless steel is used in corrosive or washdown environments. Aluminum is used where weight reduction is a priority. Material is specified in the customer drawing.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">Can you match an existing retainer plate if I don't have the original drawing?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Yes. We can measure an existing retainer plate and produce a reverse-engineered drawing for review before machining. This is common for replacement parts where the original drawing is not available.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What surface finish do you provide on bearing contact faces?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">Contact face surface finish is specified based on your bearing manufacturer's requirement. Ra 0.8 μm (N6) is typical for bearing seats. Finer finishes are available for high-precision or preloaded bearing arrangements.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-question">What batch sizes do you support?</h3>
            <p class="faq-answer">We support prototype quantities (1–10 pieces) through to batch production. Prototype samples allow verification of dimensional compliance before full batch runs. Contact us with quantity and timeline requirements for a quotation.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

